# 🔵 First Understand “Wrapped Element”

Wrapped element means:

You create a custom component
Inside it, you wrap a real HTML element.

Example:

```jsx
function Button() {
  return (
    <div>
      <button>Click</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Here:

* `Button` is custom component
* `<button>` is wrapped inside `<div>`

---

# 🔴 The Problem

If parent sends props:

```jsx
<Button type="submit" disabled />
```

Those props DO NOT automatically reach `<button>`.

Why?

Because React does NOT auto-forward props.

They stop at `Button` component.

---

# 🟢 Simple Solution: Forward Props

You must manually pass them.

---

## ✅ Step 1: Receive props

```jsx
function Button(props) {
  return (
    <div>
      <button {...props}>Click</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Now:

```jsx
<Button type="submit" disabled />
```

Becomes:

```html
<button type="submit" disabled>
```

Now props are forwarded correctly.

---

# 🧠 Flow Explanation (Very Simple)

Parent
⬇
Button component
⬇
Real HTML element

If you don’t use `{...props}`
Props stop in the middle.

---

# 🟣 More Real Example (Common in Real Projects)

Let’s say you want to add custom styling but still allow normal button props.

---

### Without Forwarding (Wrong)

```jsx
function CustomButton() {
  return <button className="btn">Click</button>;
}
```

Now:

```jsx
<CustomButton onClick={handleClick} />
```

❌ onClick will NOT work.

---

### With Forwarding (Correct)

```jsx
function CustomButton(props) {
  return (
    <button className="btn" {...props}>
      Click
    </button>
  );
}
```

Now:

* onClick works
* disabled works
* type works
* className works

Everything works.

---

# 🔥 Even Better Pattern (Destructuring)

```jsx
function CustomButton({ children, ...props }) {
  return (
    <button className="btn" {...props}>
      {children}
    </button>
  );
}
```

Now you can do:

```jsx
<CustomButton type="submit">Save</CustomButton>
```

This is clean and professional way.

---

# 🎯 Final Simple Understanding

Forwarding props means:

> Taking props from parent
> Passing them to inner HTML element
> Using `{...props}`

